{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4ff7264a-8696-4ed2-8aba-03c390a12c3c","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (libraries like `ModelContextProtocol` or `McpDotNet` handle this).\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command` with the path to the executable and drop `args`.\n\nFor a **release build**, you can use:\n\n```json\n\"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\", \"-c\", \"Release\"]\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"39ede7e0-4698-447d-a069-e6a48a45a488","outputTokens":317,"requestId":"385D:3665CC:6E6BD80:76CBC9F:6A03CFAD"},"id":"1a2d6702-dc37-4132-aae4-00d31f35d172","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:11:19.175Z","parentId":"336d5e26-8c27-4d69-ab05-94d52c55108e"}
